# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: system-f
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] In functional programming, a **generalized algebraic data type** (**GADT**, also **first-class phantom type**, **guarded recursive datatype**, or **equality-qualified type**) is a generalization of a parametric algebraic data type (ADT).
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] In a GADT, the product constructors (called data constructors in Haskell) can provide an explicit instantiation of the ADT as the type instantiation of their return value.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] This allows defining functions with a more advanced type behaviour.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] For a data constructor of Haskell 2010, the return value has the type instantiation implied by the instantiation of the ADT parameters at the constructor's application.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] They are currently implemented in the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) as a non-standard extension, used by, among others, Pugs and Darcs.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] OCaml supports GADT natively since version 4.00.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] The GHC implementation provides support for existentially quantified type parameters and for local constraints.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] An early version of generalized algebraic data types were described by Augustsson & Petersson (1994) and based on pattern matching in ALF.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] Generalized algebraic data types were introduced independently by Cheney & Hinze (2003) and prior by Xi, Chen & Chen (2003) as extensions to the algebraic data types of ML and Haskell.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] Both are essentially equivalent to each other.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] Sulzmann, Wazny & Stuckey (2006) introduced *extended algebraic data types* which combine GADTs together with the existential data types and type class constraints.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] Type inference in the absence of any programmer supplied type annotation, is undecidable and functions defined over GADTs do not admit principal types in general.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] Type reconstruction requires several design trade-offs and is an area of active research (Peyton Jones, Washburn & Weirich 2004; Peyton Jones et al.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] This major update of Scala introduced the possibility to write GADTs with the same syntax as algebraic data types, which is not the case in other programming languages according to Martin Odersky.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] Applications of GADTs include generic programming, modelling programming languages (higher-order abstract syntax), maintaining invariants in data structures, expressing constraints in embedded domain-specific languages, and modelling objects.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] An important application of GADTs is to embed higher-order abstract syntax in a type safe fashion.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] Problems would have occurred using regular algebraic data types.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] Dropping the type parameter would have made the lifted base types existentially quantified, making it impossible to write the evaluator.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] With a type parameter, it is still restricted to one base type.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] Further, ill-formed expressions such as `App (Lam (\x -> Lam (\y -> App x y))) (Lift True)` would have been possible to construct, while they are type incorrect using the GADT.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] A well-formed analogue is `App (Lam (\x -> Lam (\y -> App x y))) (Lift (\z -> True))`.
[src:system-f/generalized-algebraic-data-type] This is because the type of `x` is `Lam (a -> b)`, inferred from the type of the `Lam` data constructor.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] In mathematics, logic and philosophy of mathematics, something that is **impredicative** is a self-referencing definition.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Roughly speaking, a definition is impredicative if it invokes (mentions or quantifies over) the set being defined, or (more commonly) another set that contains the thing being defined.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] There is no generally accepted precise definition of what it means to be predicative or impredicative.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Authors have given different but related definitions.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] The opposite of impredicativity is predicativity, which essentially entails building stratified (or ramified) theories where quantification over a type at one 'level' results in types at a new, higher, level.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] A prototypical example is intuitionistic type theory, which retains ramification (without the explicit levels) so as to discard impredicativity.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] The 'levels' here correspond to the number of layers of dependency in a term definition.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Russell's paradox is a famous example of an impredicative construction—namely the set of all sets that do not contain themselves.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] The paradox is that such a set cannot exist: If it were to exist, the question could be asked whether it contains itself or not—if it does then by definition it should not, and if it does not then by definition it should.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] The greatest lower bound of a set *X*, glb(*X*), also has an impredicative definition: *y* = glb(*X*) if and only if for all elements *x* of *X*, *y* is less than or equal to *x*, and any *z* less than or equal to all elements of *X* is less than or equal to *y*.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] This definition quantifies over the set (potentially infinite, depending on the order in question) whose members are the lower bounds of *X*, one of which being the glb itself.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Hence **predicativism** would reject this definition.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] The terms "predicative" and "impredicative" were introduced by Bertrand Russell, though the meaning has changed a little since then.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Solomon Feferman provides a historical review of predicativity, connecting it to current outstanding research problems.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] The vicious circle principle was suggested by Henri Poincaré (1905–6, 1908) and Bertrand Russell in the wake of the paradoxes as a requirement on legitimate set specifications.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Sets that do not meet the requirement are called *impredicative*.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] The first modern paradox appeared with Cesare Burali-Forti's 1897 *A question on transfinite numbers* and would become known as the Burali-Forti paradox.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Georg Cantor had apparently discovered the same paradox in his (Cantor's) "naive" set theory and this become known as Cantor's paradox.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] In other words, given *f*(*a*) the function *f* is the variable and *a* is the invariant part.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] So why not substitute the value *f*(*a*) for *f* itself?
[src:system-f/impredicativity] While the problem had adverse personal consequences for both men (both had works at the printers that had to be emended), van Heijenoort observes that "The paradox shook the logicians' world, and the rumbles are still felt today. ...
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Russell's paradox, which uses the bare notions of set and element, falls squarely in the field of logic.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] The paradox was first published by Russell in *The principles of mathematics* (1903) and is discussed there in great detail ...".
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Russell, after six years of false starts, would eventually answer the matter with his 1908 theory of types by "propounding his *axiom of reducibility*.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] It says that any function is coextensive with what he calls a *predicative* function: a function in which the types of apparent variables run no higher than the types of the arguments".
[src:system-f/impredicativity] But this "axiom" was met with resistance from all quarters.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] The rejection of impredicatively defined mathematical objects (while accepting the natural numbers as classically understood) leads to the position in the philosophy of mathematics known as predicativism, advocated by Henri Poincaré and by Hermann Weyl in his *Das Kontinuum*.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Poincaré and Weyl argued that impredicative definitions are problematic only when one or more underlying sets are infinite.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Ernst Zermelo in his 1908 "A new proof of the possibility of a well-ordering" presents an entire section "b.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] *Objection concerning nonpredicative definition*" where he argued against "Poincaré (1906, p.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] 307) [who states that] a definition is 'predicative' and logically admissible only if it *excludes* all objects that are dependent upon the notion defined, that is, that can in any way be determined by it".
[src:system-f/impredicativity] He gives two examples of impredicative definitions – (i) the notion of Dedekind chains and (ii) "in analysis wherever the maximum or minimum of a previously defined "completed" set of numbers *Z* is used for further inferences.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] This happens, for example, in the well-known Cauchy proof...".
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Zermelo's example of minimum and maximum of a previously defined "completed" set of numbers reappears in Kleene 1952:42-42, where Kleene uses the example of least upper bound in his discussion of impredicative definitions; Kleene does not resolve this problem.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] In the next paragraphs he discusses Weyl's attempt in his 1918 *Das Kontinuum* (*The Continuum*) to eliminate impredicative definitions and his failure to retain the "theorem that an arbitrary non-empty set M of real numbers having an upper bound has a least upper bound (cf. also Weyl 1919)".
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Ramsey argued that "impredicative" definitions can be harmless: for instance, the definition of "tallest person in the room" is impredicative, since it depends on a set of things of which it is an element, namely the set of all persons in the room.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Concerning mathematics, an example of an impredicative definition is the smallest number in a set, which is formally defined as: *y* = min(*X*) if and only if for all elements *x* of *X*, *y* is less than or equal to *x*, and *y* is in *X*.
[src:system-f/impredicativity] Burgess (2005) discusses predicative and impredicative theories at some length, in the context of Frege's logic, Peano arithmetic, second-order arithmetic, and axiomatic set theory.
[src:system-f/jean-yves-girard] Jean-Yves Girard is an alumnus of the École normale supérieure de Saint-Cloud.
[src:system-f/jean-yves-girard] He made a name for himself in the 1970s with his proof of strong normalization in a system of second-order logic called System F.
[src:system-f/jean-yves-girard] This result gave a new proof of Takeuti's conjecture, which was proven a few years earlier by William W.
[src:system-f/jean-yves-girard] For this purpose, he introduced the notion of "reducibility candidate" ("candidat de réductibilité").
[src:system-f/jean-yves-girard] He is also credited with the discovery of Girard's paradox, linear logic, the geometry of interaction, ludics, and (satirically) the mustard watch.
[src:system-f/jean-yves-girard] He obtained the CNRS Silver Medal in 1983 and is a member of the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:system-f/parametricity] In programming language theory, **parametricity** is an abstract uniformity property enjoyed by parametrically polymorphic functions, which captures the intuition that all instances of a polymorphic function act the same way.
[src:system-f/parametricity] Consider this example, based on a set *X* and the type *T*(*X*) = [*X* → *X*] of functions from *X* to itself.
[src:system-f/parametricity] The higher-order function *twice**X* : *T*(*X*) → *T*(*X*) given by *twice**X*(*f*) = *f* ∘ *f*, is intuitively independent of the set *X*.
[src:system-f/parametricity] The family of all such functions *twice**X*, parametrized by sets *X*, is called a "parametrically polymorphic function".
[src:system-f/parametricity] We simply write **twice** for the entire family of these functions and write its type as $\forall$ *X*.
[src:system-f/parametricity] The individual functions *twice**X* are called the *components* or *instances* of the polymorphic function.
[src:system-f/parametricity] Notice that all the component functions *twice**X* act "the same way" because they are given by the same rule.
[src:system-f/parametricity] Other families of functions obtained by picking one arbitrary function from each *T*(*X*) → *T*(*X*) would not have such uniformity.
[src:system-f/parametricity] They are called "*ad hoc* polymorphic functions".
[src:system-f/parametricity] *Parametricity* is the abstract property enjoyed by the uniformly acting families such as **twice**, which distinguishes them from *ad hoc* families.
[src:system-f/parametricity] With an adequate formalization of parametricity, it is possible to prove that the parametrically polymorphic functions of type $\forall$ *X*.
[src:system-f/parametricity] The function corresponding to the natural number *n* is given by the rule *f* $\mapsto$ *f**n*, i.e., the polymorphic Church numeral for *n*.
[src:system-f/parametricity] In contrast, the collection of all *ad hoc* families would be too large to be a set.
[src:system-f/parametricity] The *parametricity theorem* was originally stated by John C.
[src:system-f/parametricity] Reynolds, who called it the *abstraction theorem*.
[src:system-f/parametricity] In his paper "Theorems for free!", Philip Wadler described an application of parametricity to derive theorems about parametrically polymorphic functions based on their types.
[src:system-f/parametricity] Parametricity is the basis for many program transformations implemented in compilers for the programming language Haskell.
[src:system-f/parametricity] These transformations were traditionally thought to be correct in Haskell because of Haskell's non-strict semantics.
[src:system-f/parametricity] Despite being a lazy evaluation programming language, Haskell does support certain primitive operations, such as the operator `seq`—that enable so-called *selective strictness*, allowing evaluation to be forced for certain expressions.
[src:system-f/parametricity] In their paper "Free theorems in the presence of *seq*", Patricia Johann and Janis Voigtlaender showed that because of the presence of these operations, the general parametricity theorem does not hold for Haskell programs; thus, these transformations are unsound in general.
[src:system-f/system-f] Whereas simply typed lambda calculus has variables ranging over terms, and binders for them, System F additionally has variables ranging over *types*, and binders for them.
[src:system-f/system-f] The upper-case $\Lambda$ is traditionally used to denote type-level functions, as opposed to the lower-case $\lambda$ which is used for value-level functions.
[src:system-f/system-f] As a term rewriting system, System F is strongly normalizing.
[src:system-f/system-f] However, type inference in System F (without explicit type annotations) is undecidable.
[src:system-f/system-f] Under the Curry–Howard isomorphism, System F corresponds to second-order propositional intuitionistic logic.
[src:system-f/system-f] System F can be seen as part of the lambda cube, together with even more expressive typed lambda calculi, including those with dependent types.
[src:system-f/system-f] According to Girard, the "F" in *System F* was picked by chance.
[src:system-f/system-f] where $\sigma ,\tau$ are types, $\alpha$ is a type variable, and $\alpha ~{\text{type}}$ in the context indicates that $\alpha$ is bound.
[src:system-f/system-f] The first rule is that of application, and the second is that of abstraction.
[src:system-f/system-f] The ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ type is defined as: $\forall \alpha .\alpha \to \alpha \to \alpha$ , where $\alpha$ is a type variable.
[src:system-f/system-f] (Note that the above two functions require *three* — not two — arguments.
[src:system-f/system-f] The latter two should be lambda expressions, but the first one should be a type.
[src:system-f/system-f] This fact is reflected in the fact that the type of these expressions is $\forall \alpha .\alpha \to \alpha \to \alpha$ ; the universal quantifier binding the α corresponds to the Λ binding the alpha in the lambda expression itself.
[src:system-f/system-f] Also, note that ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ is a convenient shorthand for $\forall \alpha .\alpha \to \alpha \to \alpha$ , but it is not a symbol of System F itself, but rather a "meta-symbol".
[src:system-f/system-f] Note that in the definitions above, ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ is a type argument to x , specifying that the other two parameters that are given to x are of type ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ .
[src:system-f/system-f] As in Church encodings, there is no need for an IFTHENELSE function as one can just use raw ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ -typed terms as decision functions.
[src:system-f/system-f] A *predicate* is a function which returns a ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ -typed value.
[src:system-f/system-f] System F allows recursive constructions to be embedded in a natural manner, related to that in Martin-Löf's type theory.
[src:system-f/system-f] Abstract structures (S) are created using *constructors*.
[src:system-f/system-f] Recursivity is manifested when S itself appears within one of the types $K_{i}$ .
[src:system-f/system-f] The System F type corresponding to this structure is $\forall \alpha .\alpha \to (\alpha \to \alpha )\to \alpha$ .
[src:system-f/system-f] If we reverse the order of the curried arguments (*i.e.,* $\forall \alpha .(\alpha \rightarrow \alpha )\rightarrow \alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ ), then the Church numeral for n is a function that takes a function f as argument and returns the nth power of f.
[src:system-f/system-f] That is to say, a Church numeral is a higher-order function – it takes a single-argument function f, and returns another single-argument function.
[src:system-f/system-f] The version of System F used in this article is as an explicitly typed, or Church-style, calculus.
[src:system-f/system-f] The typing information contained in λ-terms makes type-checking straightforward.
[src:system-f/system-f] Joe Wells (1994) settled an "embarrassing open problem" by proving that type checking is undecidable for a Curry-style variant of System F, that is, one that lacks explicit typing annotations.
[src:system-f/system-f] Wells's result implies that type inference for System F is impossible.
[src:system-f/system-f] A restriction of System F known as "Hindley–Milner", or simply "HM", does have an easy type inference algorithm and is used for many statically typed functional programming languages such as Haskell 98 and the ML family.
[src:system-f/system-f] Over time, as the restrictions of HM-style type systems have become apparent, languages have steadily moved to more expressive logics for their type systems.
[src:system-f/system-f] GHC, a Haskell compiler, goes beyond HM (as of 2008) and uses System F extended with non-syntactic type equality; non-HM features in OCaml's type system include GADT.
[src:system-f/system-f] In second-order intuitionistic logic, the second-order polymorphic lambda calculus (F2) was discovered by Girard (1972) and independently by Reynolds (1974).
[src:system-f/system-f] Girard proved the *representation theorem*: that in second-order intuitionistic predicate logic (P2), functions from the natural numbers to the natural numbers that can be proved total, form a projection from P2 into F2.
[src:system-f/system-f] Reynolds proved the *abstraction theorem*: that every term in F2 satisfies a logical relation, which can be embedded into the logical relations P2.
[src:system-f/system-f] Reynolds proved that a Girard projection followed by a Reynolds embedding form the identity, i.e., the **Girard–Reynolds isomorphism**.
[src:system-f/system-f] While System F corresponds to the first axis of Barendregt's lambda cube, **System Fω** or the **higher-order polymorphic lambda calculus** combines the first axis (polymorphism) with the second axis (type operators); it is a different, more complex system.
[src:system-f/system-f] That is, Fω is the system which allows functions from types to types where the argument (and result) may be of any order.
[src:system-f/system-f] Note that although Fω places no restrictions on the *order* of the arguments in these mappings, it does restrict the *universe* of the arguments for these mappings: they must be types rather than values.
[src:system-f/system-f] System Fω does not permit mappings from values to types (dependent types), though it does permit mappings from values to values ( $\lambda$ abstraction), mappings from types to values ( $\Lambda$ abstraction), and mappings from types to types ( $\lambda$ abstraction at the level of types).
[src:system-f/type-variable] In type theory and programming languages, a **type variable** is a mathematical variable ranging over types.
[src:system-f/type-variable] Even in programming languages that allow mutable variables, a type variable remains an abstraction, in the sense that it does not correspond to some memory locations.
[src:system-f/type-variable] Programming languages that support parametric polymorphism make use of universally quantified type variables.
[src:system-f/type-variable] Languages that support existential types make use of existentially quantified type variables.
[src:system-f/type-variable] In mathematical notation, the type of the function `id` is $\forall a.a\to a$ , where a is a type variable.
[src:system-f/type-variable] In generic programming, a **type parameter** or **template parameter** is used to denote the type(s) that may be consumed.
[src:system-f/type-variable] These type parameters are placeholders for types to be specified later, allowing for code to work with different types while remaining type-safe.
[src:system-f/type-variable] Type parameters are typically written as a single capital letter.
[src:system-f/type-variable] In some languages, these can be specified to have default type parameters.
[src:system-f/type-variable] Some languages additionally offer a form of constraining these type parameters, called type classes.
[src:system-f/type-variable] C++ offers concepts and `requires` clauses, C#, Kotlin and Rust offer `where` clauses, while Java has `extends` and `super` qualifiers.
[src:system-f/type-variable] Go interfaces also constrain a type such that it must implement certain methods.
[src:system-f/type-variable] Additionally, Java offers wildcard type parameters to allow for variances of any parametrisations of a generic type.
[src:system-f/type-variable] These are denoted `?`, for example `List<?>`.
[src:system-f/type-variable] This exists in Kotlin as well, but denoted with `*` instead.
[src:system-f/type-variable] In Rust, a generic type parameter can be left unspecified for the compiler to interpret using `_`, called an "inferred type" (for example `Vec<_>`).
[src:system-f/type-variable] In languages with dynamic typing, although type annotations may not be a core part of the language, some features may be provided to emulate them.
[src:system-f/type-variable] For example, in Python, type variables can still be represented and specified using the class `typing.TypeVar`.
